ERL_NIF_TERM enif_schedule_dirty_nif(ErlNifEnv* env, int flags, ERL_NIF_TERM (*fp)(ErlNifEnv* env, int argc, const ERL_NIF_TERM argv[]), int argc, const ERL_NIF_TERM argv[])
.br
.RS
.LP
Schedule dirty NIF \fIfp\fR\& to execute a long-running operation\&. The \fIflags\fR\& argument must be set to either \fIERL_NIF_DIRTY_JOB_CPU_BOUND\fR\& if the job is expected to be primarily CPU-bound, or \fIERL_NIF_DIRTY_JOB_IO_BOUND\fR\& for jobs that will be I/O-bound\&. The \fIargc\fR\& and \fIargv\fR\& arguments can either be the originals passed into the calling NIF, or they can be values created by the calling NIF\&. The calling NIF must use the return value of \fIenif_schedule_dirty_nif\fR\& as its own return value\&.
.LP
Be aware that \fIenif_schedule_dirty_nif\fR\&, as its name implies, only schedules the dirty NIF for future execution\&. The calling NIF does not block waiting for the dirty NIF to execute and return, which means that the calling NIF can\&'t expect to receive the dirty NIF return value and use it for further operations\&.
.LP
A dirty NIF may not invoke the \fBenif_make_badarg\fR\& to raise an exception\&. If it wishes to return an exception, the dirty NIF should pass a regular result indicating the exception details to its finalizer, and allow the finalizer to raise the exception on its behalf\&.
.LP

.RS -4
.B
Note:
.RE
This function is available only when the emulator is configured with dirty schedulers enabled\&. This feature is currently disabled by default\&. To determine whether the dirty NIF API is available, native code can check to see if the C preprocessor macro \fIERL_NIF_DIRTY_SCHEDULER_SUPPORT\fR\& is defined\&.

.RE
.LP
.B
ERL_NIF_TERM enif_schedule_dirty_nif_finalizer(ErlNifEnv* env, ERL_NIF_TERM result, ERL_NIF_TERM (*fp)(ErlNifEnv* env, ERL_NIF_TERM result))
.br
.RS
.LP
When a dirty NIF finishes executing, it must schedule a finalizer function to return its result to the original NIF caller\&. The dirty NIF passes \fIresult\fR\& as the value it wants the finalizer to use as the return value\&. The \fIfp\fR\& argument is a pointer to the finalizer function\&. The NIF API provides the \fB enif_dirty_nif_finalizer\fR\& function that can be used as a finalizer that simply returns its \fIresult\fR\& argument\&. You are also free to write your own custom finalizer that uses \fIresult\fR\& to derive a different return value, or ignores \fIresult\fR\& entirely and returns a completely different value\&.
.LP
Without exception, all dirty NIFs must invoke \fIenif_schedule_dirty_nif_finalizer\fR\& to complete their execution\&.
.LP

.RS -4
.B
Note:
.RE
This function is available only when the emulator is configured with dirty schedulers enabled\&. This feature is currently disabled by default\&. To determine whether the dirty NIF API is available, native code can check to see if the C preprocessor macro \fIERL_NIF_DIRTY_SCHEDULER_SUPPORT\fR\& is defined\&.

